Here are the comprehensive project building notes for the LeetCode Metrics App from Love Babbar's (CodeHelp) web development bootcamp series [00:01:22].

This hands-on capstone project synthesizes everything learned about DOM Manipulation, Asynchronous JavaScript (async/await), the fetch API, CSS Flexbox/Grid, and Circular Progress Trackers into a live, production-grade utility interface [00:01:22].

1. Core Project Architectural Objective
The goal is to engineer a clean, high-performance client interface where users can type any valid LeetCode username profile handle, hit search, and dynamically extract, parse, and render real-time problem-solving statistics [00:02:22].

Core Features Included:
Real-time third-party REST API integration handling JSON stream feeds [00:02:22].

Dynamic user interface updates based on fetched data profiles.

Circular CSS progress ring visualizations mapping solved problem ratios across Easy, Medium, and Hard categories [00:02:22].

Complete search state handling, including loading animation states, validation checks, and error boundaries.

2. Structure Blueprint (index.html)
HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>LeetCode Metrics Application</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="app-container">
        <h1>LeetCode Metrics Tracker</h1>
        
        <div class="search-box">
            <input type="text" id="username-input" placeholder="Enter LeetCode username...">
            <button id="search-btn">Search Profile</button>
        </div>

        <div class="dashboard-wrapper">
            <div class="stats-container">
                <div class="card easy-card">
                    <h3>Easy</h3>
                    <div class="progress-circle" id="easy-circle">
                        <span id="easy-solved">0/0</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card medium-card">
                    <h3>Medium</h3>
                    <div class="progress-circle" id="medium-circle">
                        <span id="medium-solved">0/0</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card hard-card">
                    <h3>Hard</h3>
                    <div class="progress-circle" id="hard-circle">
                        <span id="hard-solved">0/0</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="meta-container">
                <div class="meta-card">Total Solved: <span id="total-solved">0</span></div>
                <div class="meta-card">Acceptance Rate: <span id="acceptance-rate">0%</span></div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
3. Presentation Architecture Design (style.css)
To render circular progress indicators cleanly without complex heavy charts or libraries, use a CSS background gradient technique (conic-gradient) managed dynamically by JavaScript variables.

CSS
:root {
    --bg-primary: #1a1a1a;
    --bg-card: #262626;
    --text-main: #ffffff;
    --color-easy: #00b8a3;
    --color-medium: #ffc01e;
    --color-hard: #ef4743;
}

body {
    background-color: var(--bg-primary);
    color: var(--text-main);
    font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    min-height: 100vh;
    margin: 0;
}

.app-container {
    background-color: var(--bg-card);
    padding: 2.5rem;
    border-radius: 12px;
    box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
    max-width: 600px;
    width: 100%;
    text-align: center;
}

.search-box {
    display: flex;
    gap: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

.search-box input {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 12px;
    border-radius: 6px;
    border: 1px solid #404040;
    background-color: #333333;
    color: white;
}

.search-box button {
    padding: 12px 24px;
    background-color: #f7931e;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 6px;
    color: white;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-weight: bold;
}

.stats-container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 20px;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

.card {
    background: #1e1e1e;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    flex: 1;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
}

/* Circular Dashboard Blueprint Pattern */
.progress-circle {
    width: 100px;
    height: 100px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    /* Default dark track circle fallback */
    background: radial-gradient(closest-side, #1e1e1e 79%, transparent 80%),
                conic-gradient(var(--fill-color, #444) 0deg, #333 0deg);
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    margin-top: 10px;
}
4. Logical Interaction Layer (script.js)
This layer hooks into user input events, manages network states via fetch, extracts sub-property fields from the response data, and targets DOM structural elements to update the interface.

JavaScript
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
    const searchButton = document.getElementById("search-btn");
    const usernameInput = document.getElementById("username-input");
    
    const easyCircle = document.getElementById("easy-circle");
    const mediumCircle = document.getElementById("medium-circle");
    const hardCircle = document.getElementById("hard-circle");

    const easySolvedText = document.getElementById("easy-solved");
    const mediumSolvedText = document.getElementById("medium-solved");
    const hardSolvedText = document.getElementById("hard-solved");

    const totalSolvedText = document.getElementById("total-solved");
    const acceptanceRateText = document.getElementById("acceptance-rate");

    // 1. Structural Helper: Validate input string criteria
    function validateUsername(username) {
        if (username.trim() === "") {
            alert("Username handle field cannot be left blank.");
            return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

    // 2. Structural Helper: Update progress display elements inside the DOM
    function updateProgressRing(circleElement, textElement, solved, total, cssColorVar) {
        // Enforce safe boundary limits to prevent Division-by-Zero runtime crashes
        const ratioPercentage = total > 0 ? (solved / total) * 100 : 0;
        
        textElement.textContent = `${solved}/${total}`;
        
        // Dynamically overwrite conic-gradient angles via inline element styles
        circleElement.style.background = `
            radial-gradient(closest-side, #1e1e1e 79%, transparent 80%),
            conic-gradient(${cssColorVar} ${ratioPercentage * 3.6}deg, #333 0deg)
        `;
    }

    // 3. Core Network Pipeline Engine Block
    async function fetchLeetCodeMetrics(username) {
        // Fallback pipeline endpoint proxy targeting standard open-source API routers
        const targetUrl = `https://leetcode-api-faisalshohag.vercel.app/${username}`;
        
        try {
            searchButton.textContent = "Searching...";
            searchButton.disabled = true;

            let response = await fetch(targetUrl);
            if (!response.ok) {
                throw new Error("Target profile resource record not found.");
            }

            let dataPayload = await response.json();
            console.log("Harvested payload statistics stream:", dataPayload);

            // 4. Updating the Dashboard View
            totalSolvedText.textContent = dataPayload.totalSolved || 0;
            acceptanceRateText.textContent = `${dataPayload.acceptanceRate || 0}%`;

            // Update respective Easy, Medium, Hard category tracking rings safely
            updateProgressRing(easyCircle, easySolvedText, dataPayload.easySolved, dataPayload.totalEasy, "var(--color-easy)");
            updateProgressRing(mediumCircle, mediumSolvedText, dataPayload.mediumSolved, dataPayload.totalMedium, "var(--color-medium)");
            updateProgressRing(hardCircle, hardSolvedText, dataPayload.hardSolved, dataPayload.totalHard, "var(--color-hard)");

        } catch (error) {
            alert(`Execution halted cleanly: ${error.message}`);
        } finally {
            searchButton.textContent = "Search Profile";
            searchButton.disabled = false;
        }
    }

    // 5. Wire Event Listener Attachments
    searchButton.addEventListener("click", () => {
        const username = usernameInput.value;
        if (validateUsername(username)) {
            fetchLeetCodeMetrics(username);
        }
    });
});
5. Summary Key Learning Takeaways
Input Validation & Guard Clauses: Implement strict data checking on inputs before firing network request pipelines to save browser resources.

Inline CSS Variables Override: Directly using standard inline styles to override specific CSS constants (conic-gradient calculations) enables deep data visualization effects without needing external graphing libraries.

Graceful Asynchronous Flows: Using try-catch-finally structures ensures that application state animations (such as disabling or modifying button text) roll back cleanly to their default states if a network error occurs.